UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438788790071X
AB  - This paper considers the pattern of growth of less developed regions (LDRs) vs. more developed regions (MDRs) in Yugoslavia in the period 1952–1983. It evaluates the growth using the three possible policy-makers' criteria: the Pareto criterion (rate of growth of both LDRs and MDRs should increase), the Rawls criterion (rate of growth of MDRs may increase so long as it raises that of LDRs), and the Verkhovensky criterion (positive difference between the rate of growth on LDRs and MDRs should be maximized). The pattern of growth in Yugoslavia is found to have changed after major economic and political decentralization in 1965: it is superior to the pattern in the previous period only in the Verkhovensky sense.
